1
00:00:00,500 --> 00:00:02,780
Have a look at this Heikin ashi chart.

2
00:00:02,780 --> 00:00:06,899
We have an aggressive down move, then a quick
reversal to the upside.

3
00:00:06,899 --> 00:00:12,769
But, there’s a specific price action signal,
during this period, which revealed sellers

4
00:00:12,769 --> 00:00:15,099
were no longer in control.

5
00:00:15,099 --> 00:00:16,230
Can you spot it?

6
00:00:16,230 --> 00:00:19,030
It’s right in the middle.

7
00:00:19,030 --> 00:00:25,250
3 consecutive lower wicks which revealed bullish
pressure, around this price level.

8
00:00:25,250 --> 00:00:30,800
This is one of the best ways to anticipate
a change in momentum, with a low risk, a potential

9
00:00:30,800 --> 00:00:31,869
high reward.

10
00:00:31,869 --> 00:00:33,860
Let’s talk about it.

11
00:00:33,860 --> 00:00:39,450
You know the drill, like, subscribe, and stick
around for the full video.

12
00:00:39,450 --> 00:00:46,469
Buying/selling pressure zones
Candlesticks wicks can tell you a lot about

13
00:00:46,469 --> 00:00:51,660
the psychology of market participants and
it definitely must play an important role

14
00:00:51,660 --> 00:00:53,910
in your price action analysis.

15
00:00:53,910 --> 00:01:00,230
In a Heikin-Ashi chart, large wicks can indicate
a high level of volatility or uncertainty

16
00:01:00,230 --> 00:01:01,230
in the market.

17
00:01:01,230 --> 00:01:07,200
For example, if the high and low prices for
a particular time frame are significantly

18
00:01:07,200 --> 00:01:12,650
different from the open and close prices,
it may indicate that there was a lot of buying

19
00:01:12,650 --> 00:01:16,130
and selling activity during that period.

20
00:01:16,130 --> 00:01:22,180
This could be a sign that the market is indecisive
or that there is a lack of clear direction.

21
00:01:22,180 --> 00:01:27,400
On the other hand, if the wicks are small
or absent, it may indicate that the market

22
00:01:27,400 --> 00:01:28,640
is more stable.

23
00:01:28,640 --> 00:01:34,000
A series of candlesticks with long wicks on
a Heikin Ashi chart is something you should

24
00:01:34,000 --> 00:01:40,520
paying attention to, because this can potentially
indicate a change in trend.

25
00:01:40,520 --> 00:01:46,790
So the plan is to look for periods when momentum
is fading away, and a potential trend change

26
00:01:46,790 --> 00:01:48,219
is on the way.

27
00:01:48,219 --> 00:01:53,909
In a Heikin-Ashi chart, trend changes can
be identified by looking at the shape, size

28
00:01:53,909 --> 00:01:56,690
and direction of the candlesticks.

29
00:01:56,690 --> 00:02:02,649
For example, in this chart we are in in an
uptrend, but the candlesticks start to become

30
00:02:02,649 --> 00:02:05,969
smaller and more evenly sized.

31
00:02:05,969 --> 00:02:12,480
This may indicate that the uptrend is losing
momentum and a trend change is imminent.

32
00:02:12,480 --> 00:02:18,349
The same here, the market was in a downtrend
and the candlesticks started to become smaller

33
00:02:18,349 --> 00:02:24,010
and more uneven, and this is the first sign
that the downtrend is losing strength and

34
00:02:24,010 --> 00:02:26,780
a trend change is coming.

35
00:02:26,780 --> 00:02:33,410
Consecutive candle wicks during this period
reveals bullish or bearish pressure.

36
00:02:33,410 --> 00:02:41,190
Now, a strong Heikin Ashi pressure zone is
not defined just by one candle with a big

37
00:02:41,190 --> 00:02:42,190
wick.

38
00:02:42,190 --> 00:02:47,519
A single price bar might not be sufficiently
reliable for a trading setup.

39
00:02:47,519 --> 00:02:52,680
To filter false signals, you must identify
a group of candlesticks.

40
00:02:52,680 --> 00:02:58,629
Therefore, instead of a single Heikin Ashi
candle, look for at least 2 consecutive bars

41
00:02:58,629 --> 00:03:04,430
with overlapping upper or lower shadows, more
even better.

42
00:03:04,430 --> 00:03:09,769
Remember, wicks indicate potential buying
or selling pressure.

43
00:03:09,769 --> 00:03:14,970
When these shadows overlap, they create a
price zone that is more likely to exhibit

44
00:03:14,970 --> 00:03:18,230
the buying or selling pressure you anticipate.

45
00:03:18,230 --> 00:03:22,050
Here’s a bullish pressure zone.

46
00:03:22,050 --> 00:03:23,050
1.

47
00:03:23,050 --> 00:03:28,450
We have 3 consecutive Heikin ashi bars with
overlapping lower shadows.

48
00:03:28,450 --> 00:03:29,450
2.

49
00:03:29,450 --> 00:03:34,470
We mark the zone, by outlining the lowest
low and the highest closing price

50
00:03:34,470 --> 00:03:35,470
3.

51
00:03:35,470 --> 00:03:40,629
This area is the bullish Pressure Zone
Now, very important.

52
00:03:40,629 --> 00:03:43,909
Small shadows can create unreliable pressure
zones.

53
00:03:43,909 --> 00:03:48,440
The wicks of these candles must be somewhat
larger in size.

54
00:03:48,440 --> 00:03:55,370
I mean I wouldn’t say this is a strong buying
zone, the wicks are too small.

55
00:03:55,370 --> 00:03:57,340
This one is more significant.

56
00:03:57,340 --> 00:04:01,829
And here’s a bearish pressure zone.

57
00:04:01,829 --> 00:04:02,829
1.

58
00:04:02,829 --> 00:04:08,069
We have minimum 3 consecutive Heikin ashi
bars with overlapping upper shadows.

59
00:04:08,069 --> 00:04:09,069
2.

60
00:04:09,069 --> 00:04:13,870
We outline the highest high and the lowest
closing price within this sequence

61
00:04:13,870 --> 00:04:14,870
3.

62
00:04:14,870 --> 00:04:21,040
This area is the bearish Pressure Zone
It is also important to note that these consecutive

63
00:04:21,040 --> 00:04:24,720
wicks in Heikin Ashi charts should not be
used in isolation.

64
00:04:24,720 --> 00:04:30,800
It is always a good idea to use multiple tools
and indicators, and to carefully consider

65
00:04:30,800 --> 00:04:36,480
the overall market context, when trying to
identify the potential trend reversals or

66
00:04:36,480 --> 00:04:40,180
changes in market sentiment.

67
00:04:40,180 --> 00:04:44,979
Support/resistance confluence

68
00:04:44,979 --> 00:04:50,110
So instead of taking signals and trades all
over the place, the better trades usually

69
00:04:50,110 --> 00:04:55,560
happen at key price levels, and are followed
by an opposite color candle.

70
00:04:55,560 --> 00:04:58,140
Here’s the bullish Pressure Zone.

71
00:04:58,140 --> 00:05:03,330
These consecutive Heikin Ashi wicks, indicate
sellers are losing their strength.

72
00:05:03,330 --> 00:05:06,080
On its own, this zone is not relevant.

73
00:05:06,080 --> 00:05:11,940
But it appeared at an area of previous resistance,
which turned into support.

74
00:05:11,940 --> 00:05:14,139
And this is important.

75
00:05:14,139 --> 00:05:20,169
These candles where followed by a green Heikin
ashi one, which also has a lower wick.

76
00:05:20,169 --> 00:05:22,580
This is a weak buy signal.

77
00:05:22,580 --> 00:05:28,889
The strongest signals appear when a green
candle with no lower wick appears.

78
00:05:28,889 --> 00:05:35,630
A good entry area is after you have the first
green Heikin ashi candle, rejecting the bullish

79
00:05:35,630 --> 00:05:37,250
pressure zone.

80
00:05:37,250 --> 00:05:43,870
Stop loss placement is obvious, below the
zone and you target double the amount you’ve

81
00:05:43,870 --> 00:05:44,870
risked.

82
00:05:44,870 --> 00:05:51,320
Here’s Pound dollar, on the hourly time
frame, with several bullish and bearish pressure

83
00:05:51,320 --> 00:05:52,720
zones.

84
00:05:52,720 --> 00:05:55,960
First one is bullish zone, right here.

85
00:05:55,960 --> 00:06:01,790
3 consecutive candles with lower wicks, followed
by a green candle.

86
00:06:01,790 --> 00:06:08,310
This is a weak signal, because the signal
didn’t appear at a clear support level.

87
00:06:08,310 --> 00:06:10,480
The second signal was here.

88
00:06:10,480 --> 00:06:14,940
A bearish pressure zone, which was located
around the same area.

89
00:06:14,940 --> 00:06:21,790
A previous support turned into resistance,
and multiple Heikin ashi wicks.

90
00:06:21,790 --> 00:06:26,560
We have a short trade signal when a red HA
candle forms.

91
00:06:26,560 --> 00:06:34,440
Stop goes above the pressure zone and as usual,
you go for a risk to reward ratio of 2.

92
00:06:34,440 --> 00:06:39,729
And I see another bullish zone, again, around
the same area.

93
00:06:39,729 --> 00:06:46,300
Previous resistance turned once again in support,
consecutive long wicks, so this was a good

94
00:06:46,300 --> 00:06:51,330
opportunity to buy when a green Heikin ashi
formed.

95
00:06:51,330 --> 00:06:56,639
We even had a green candle with no lower wick,
which is the strongest signal.

96
00:06:56,639 --> 00:07:03,169
Again, stop loss below the zone, and you go
for a risk to reward ratio of 2.

97
00:07:03,169 --> 00:07:08,849
Now, as a side note, you decide how you want
to manage your trade.

98
00:07:08,849 --> 00:07:11,710
I recommend to wait for the trade to unfold.

99
00:07:11,710 --> 00:07:16,389
But, if you want to minimize risk, when the
Heiken ashi candles change color, you may

100
00:07:16,389 --> 00:07:22,509
also decide to move your stop to breakeven,
or you may even decide to close 50% of your

101
00:07:22,509 --> 00:07:28,509
the trade manually if a red candle with no
upper wick appears.

102
00:07:28,509 --> 00:07:31,410
There is no best way to manage your trade.

103
00:07:31,410 --> 00:07:36,479
In some cases, it’s better not to close
the trade when an opposite candle appear.

104
00:07:36,479 --> 00:07:45,020
In other cases, this action will preserve
your profit.

105
00:07:45,020 --> 00:07:49,849
VWAP confluence
One of my favorite ways to trade bullish and

106
00:07:49,849 --> 00:07:54,039
bearish Heikin ashi zones is with weekly VWAP.

107
00:07:54,039 --> 00:07:56,449
Not many traders are using the weekly VWAP.

108
00:07:56,449 --> 00:08:00,430
They don’t even know it’s possible to
add it on their charts.

109
00:08:00,430 --> 00:08:06,330
But this is one of the most reliable tools,
offering dynamic support and resistance.

110
00:08:06,330 --> 00:08:13,200
VWAP line that acts as a support if the price
is trading above it and as a resistance if

111
00:08:13,200 --> 00:08:15,430
the price is trading below.

112
00:08:15,430 --> 00:08:21,409
The advantage of this strategy is that it
places less emphasis on the length of a single

113
00:08:21,409 --> 00:08:25,699
shadow and instead focuses on multiple shadows.

114
00:08:25,699 --> 00:08:32,219
You want to find bullish pressure zones, above
the weekly VWAP and bearish pressure zones

115
00:08:32,219 --> 00:08:34,360
below it.

116
00:08:34,360 --> 00:08:37,950
In this example, I see a very good signal.

117
00:08:37,950 --> 00:08:44,269
First, as price is trading above the weekly
VWAP, you need to find a buy zone.

118
00:08:44,269 --> 00:08:46,450
Which is right here.

119
00:08:46,450 --> 00:08:52,910
Multiple red Heikin ashi candles with lower
wicks, right at the VWAP line.

120
00:08:52,910 --> 00:09:01,000
And as another layer of confluence, I also
see this support or demand zone, right here.

121
00:09:01,000 --> 00:09:04,339
Stop below the VWAP and below the multiple
wicks.

122
00:09:04,339 --> 00:09:09,020
And you take the profit at the next major
resistance level.

123
00:09:09,020 --> 00:09:13,850
We trade GBP/JPY, on the M15 time frame.

124
00:09:13,850 --> 00:09:20,790
Price is below the weekly VWAP, so the plan
is short the currency pair at a bearish pressure

125
00:09:20,790 --> 00:09:22,250
zone.

126
00:09:22,250 --> 00:09:28,270
Which is here, a tripe wick zone, right below
the VWAP line.

127
00:09:28,270 --> 00:09:36,040
This area is an important one because I also
see a support zone, turning into resistance.

128
00:09:36,040 --> 00:09:39,140
Multiple layers of confluence around the same
area.

129
00:09:39,140 --> 00:09:41,899
So, we found our value zone.

130
00:09:41,899 --> 00:09:48,600
The next red candle after the pressure zone
is our trigger to place a short position.

131
00:09:48,600 --> 00:09:54,459
Stop loss above the wicks and take profit
at next swing low in the price structure.

132
00:09:54,459 --> 00:10:02,530
Now, I suspect our entry level also aligns
with a Fibonacci level.

133
00:10:02,530 --> 00:10:03,589
Just as I thought!

134
00:10:03,589 --> 00:10:06,170
It was the 50% Fib retracement.

135
00:10:06,170 --> 00:10:09,730
Another layer of confluence.

136
00:10:09,730 --> 00:10:14,720
Psychological numbers

137
00:10:14,720 --> 00:10:20,770
Heikin Ashi pressure zones work extremely
well in combination with psychological numbers.

138
00:10:20,770 --> 00:10:26,170
Have you ever wondered why prices tend to
stall at certain levels in the market?

139
00:10:26,170 --> 00:10:31,640
Is this just a coincidence or is there a valid
reason behind this happening?

140
00:10:31,640 --> 00:10:37,970
Well, this phenomenon may actually be explained
based on the psychology of traders.

141
00:10:37,970 --> 00:10:44,630
As humans, we tend to think in terms of whole,
round numbers rather than in terms of uneven

142
00:10:44,630 --> 00:10:47,100
random numbers.

143
00:10:47,100 --> 00:10:52,500
Psychological numbers, also known as "round
numbers," are numbers that end in zero, such

144
00:10:52,500 --> 00:10:55,139
as 50 or 100.

145
00:10:55,139 --> 00:11:01,260
These levels go under the radar of many traders,
but these are very important in trading because

146
00:11:01,260 --> 00:11:04,790
they are often used as reference points.

147
00:11:04,790 --> 00:11:09,060
Traders are more likely to take action when
prices reach these levels.

148
00:11:09,060 --> 00:11:15,579
They are more likely to place orders or set
limits at round numbers, which can create

149
00:11:15,579 --> 00:11:21,060
additional demand or supply at these levels.

150
00:11:21,060 --> 00:11:24,329
In this chart, I see a bullish pressure zone.

151
00:11:24,329 --> 00:11:32,000
3 red Heikin ashi candles, with lower wicks,
forming at a round number.

152
00:11:32,000 --> 00:11:36,010
We even have a support level in this area.

153
00:11:36,010 --> 00:11:41,779
This is a good opportunity to place a buy
trade.

154
00:11:41,779 --> 00:11:46,170
This strategy is quite versatile and you can
trade on any time frame.

155
00:11:46,170 --> 00:11:50,190
I must say, I prefer it on higher time frames.

156
00:11:50,190 --> 00:11:54,880
By looking at higher time frames, you can
get a sense of the overall direction of the

157
00:11:54,880 --> 00:12:01,350
market with the help of Heikin Ashi and at
the same time, you identify pressure zones

158
00:12:01,350 --> 00:12:05,820
that may not be visible on shorter time frames.

159
00:12:05,820 --> 00:12:10,769
One of the main benefits of using higher time
frames for finding pressure zones is that

160
00:12:10,769 --> 00:12:15,280
they can help you filter out the short-term
noise.

161
00:12:15,280 --> 00:12:23,410
For example, here we are looking at the H4
time frame, First, we see fewer price fluctuations

162
00:12:23,410 --> 00:12:30,029
compared to someone looking at a 5-minute
chart, and is easier to identify major support

163
00:12:30,029 --> 00:12:33,190
and resistance levels.

164
00:12:33,190 --> 00:12:38,660
Consecutive wicks on lower time frames are
quite common, it happens all the time.

165
00:12:38,660 --> 00:12:43,050
But on higher time frames, it has more relevance.

166
00:12:43,050 --> 00:12:47,820
And on higher time frames, psychological numbers
are more obvious.

167
00:12:47,820 --> 00:12:54,000
Usually the more zeroes at the end of the
price, the stronger the psychological level.

168
00:12:54,000 --> 00:12:57,560
In this chart, we have a perfect, text book
example.

169
00:12:57,560 --> 00:13:06,320
3 consecutive wicks forming our bullish pressure
zone, appearing at a major round number, 200.

170
00:13:06,320 --> 00:13:13,279
I will take this buy trade every time I’ll
see it.

171
00:13:13,279 --> 00:13:18,820
As you can see, the location of the pressure
zones in the market is probably the most important

172
00:13:18,820 --> 00:13:24,350
factor to consider when trading, as it can
provide context and will help you determine

173
00:13:24,350 --> 00:13:27,800
the likelihood of the signal being accurate.

174
00:13:27,800 --> 00:13:34,209
For example, a bullish pressure zone that
occurs at a key support level is more reliable

175
00:13:34,209 --> 00:13:40,529
than a zone that forms at a resistance level,
because the support level suggests that there

176
00:13:40,529 --> 00:13:44,480
may be greater demand at that price.

177
00:13:44,480 --> 00:13:50,610
The location of the pressure zone can also
be important in the context of trend analysis.

178
00:13:50,610 --> 00:13:56,790
A buy zone that occurs during an uptrend is
more reliable than one that occurs during

179
00:13:56,790 --> 00:14:02,640
a downtrend, as it is in line with the overall
direction of the market.

180
00:14:02,640 --> 00:14:07,399
Follow these rules, find the zones on a higher
time frame, and you’ll see you’ll have

181
00:14:07,399 --> 00:15:01,300
stronger and more reliable signals.

182
00:15:01,300 --> 00:15:58,209
Now, this strategy works perfect in combination
with supply and demand levels.

183
00:15:58,209 --> 00:16:03,290
If you want to learn to trade them on Heikin
Ashi charts, and not on classic candlestick

184
00:16:03,290 --> 00:16:06,970
charts, you definitely must watch this video.

185
00:16:06,970 --> 00:16:12,699
And also check out our academy program, if
you want to further level up your trading.

186
00:16:12,699 --> 00:16:13,269
Until next time!

